review_blob: Hands down the worst porter Ive ever had. Picked up a 6 pack of cans...drain poured them all. The beer lacks identity: Is this a brown ipa? A sour porter? If you didnt tell me it was a porter, I would have guessed an over-hopped brown ale. Thin mouth feel, under carbed (even for a porter), off-putting aftertaste. The bitterness needs some smokiness or chocolate to off-set it, the hops are too prominent. Theres also a strange sourness that distracts me from trying to enjoy it. Definitely not recommended. So bad I cancelled my trip to the brewery. Buyer beware!

Resin, floral, grass, citrus, earthy. Nice dank aroma. Hits hard up front with a nice blend of floral hops and bitterness. Perfect alcohol burn. Lingers long on the palette. Really, really solid dips.
Caramel, leather, raisin. Awesome rye punch. Nice alcohol burn on the back. Very sweet.
beer_name: Bear Republic Hop Rod Rye Ale

review_blob: 2011 Bottle. Awesome head retention. Nice spicy smell. Very light, clean finish. Dark cherry, vanilla, mineral finish. Probably wouldnt cellar again, better fresh.

To be fair, smoked beers are tough to perfect...heres another casualty. Expected more from a Backstage release, but it was thin, unbalanced, and obnoxious. The overwhelming imitation liquid smoke flavor overpowered the subtleties of one of the best Porters on the market. Maybe a BA version could work? In the meantime, Ill be using the rest of mine for a marinade...Mole Sauce anyone?

Dreams do come true. My two favorite things in the world, bourbon and Reds Rye, finally together. Little sweet, and the barrel aging really knocks the bitterness off, which sucks. Would love to try this again dry hopped with Simcoe (hint, hint).
Not a fruit beer drinker...this one was a gift. Not bad, but way too sweet. Nice strawberry flavor, clean finish and perfect carbonation. All in all drinkable, but probably wouldnt seek it out.
beer_name: Samuel Smiths Organic  Strawberry Fruit Beer

review_blob: Served just above room temp in a snifter. Sweet, malty aroma. Beautiful tan head and lacing. The bitterness stands out immediately. Very creamy mouth feel; viscous. Honestly a strange stout, bitter yet sticky sweet, dark chocolate, faint burnt taste on the back. Looking forward to aging a few bottles, because this beer begs for it.
Slight floral and citrus aroma, very little carb but nice white lacing. Honey sweet on the front, finishes bitter and balanced. Little melon, malt, pine. Pleasantly complex.

Am I sucking on a Yankee Candle? Did Atwater just pour Hersheys Syrup in a Bud Light? This is the worst porter Ive ever had. Horrible imitation vanilla flavor, and by java did they mean Maxwell House? Very thin mouth feel, with a nauseating aftertaste. My first true drain pour.
Pitch black, chewy BBA goodness. Spice, licorice, vanilla, mocha, bark/earthy undertones. Very strong alcohol on the front and the back...just constant booziness actually. Love it.

#1 Desert Island Beer. I cried when Founders made it seasonal...

Stunning blend of floral hops and bitterness. Complex yet clean and crisp. Carmel sweetness, with layered levels of spice. This is the perfect beer!

The Holy Grail of BBA Stouts. Words cannot do this beer justice, so Im not even going to try.

Each bottle should come with a new pair of underwear.

Heady Topper lived up to the hype. Fantastic IIPA. What can be said about it that hasnt already been said? Its the perfect beer. Even the can is a work of art.

Insane peach/orange color, ridiculously dank aroma, and an orgasmic blend of hops. Perfect amount of bitterness, finishes clean with a pleasant floral aftertaste. Considered moving to Vermont after the last sip. Cheers.

The perfect beer? Quite possibly. Tasted along side KBS and blew it out of the water. Huge coffee wave on the front, almost mocha. Velvety, chocolately, the perfect amount of char/smokiness. Bourbon comes through nicely for a 2012, and last the whole time. Great throat burn, soothed by the intense vanilla and buttery sweetness. Thick 1/4 tan head, held for a couple sips before the glass turned to that beautiful used motor oil look. Highly recommended beer.
beer_name: Goose Island Bourbon County Stout - Coffee

review_blob: Strong offering from Bells, one of my favorites. Takes a lot of honey to make it shine through the way it does. Poor head retention, but somewhat expected in a DIPA of this nature. Strong floral, citrus, piney notes. Pleasant alcohol burn. Really enjoy this beer served room temp.
Little thin, definitely lacking in the bourbon department. Great prune finish, nice coffee flavor. Surprising long lasting on the pallet.
